SECTION 22 — BYTECODE FORMAT

The seng bytecode format, identified by the file extension ".sec" and the
magic bytes "SENG", is an original specification created by NoCorps.org build by KANAGARAJ-M. You
are free to write tools, utilities, or applications that read, write, analyse,
or process the .sec bytecode format, provided that such tools are compatible
with the official specification and that you acknowledge the origin of the
format in your tool's documentation. NoCorps.org build by KANAGARAJ-M reserves the right to evolve
the bytecode format in future versions. Future versions of the bytecode format
will be assigned new version numbers and may not be backward-compatible with
.sec files compiled by earlier versions of the seng compiler.

SECTION 23 — LANGUAGE SPECIFICATION

The seng language specification, including its keyword set, grammar rules,
operator precedence, expression syntax, statement forms, type system, and
runtime behaviour as implemented in the reference interpreter, constitutes
the normative definition of the seng language. NoCorps.org build by KANAGARAJ-M reserves the right
to make additions, changes, or clarifications to the language specification
in future versions. Where possible, changes will be designed to maintain
backward compatibility with existing seng source programs. However, no
guarantee of backward compatibility is made for major version releases.

SECTION 24 — SECURITY DISCLOSURE POLICY

If you discover a security vulnerability in the seng programming language,
its interpreter, compiler, virtual machine, or any associated tools, you are
encouraged to practise responsible disclosure. Please report security issues
directly to NoCorps.org build by KANAGARAJ-M through the official contact channels available at
nocorps.org. Allow a reasonable amount of time (typically 90 days) for
the issue to be investigated and addressed before public disclosure. Security
researchers who responsibly report genuine vulnerabilities will be credited
in the release notes of the version that addresses the vulnerability, unless
they prefer to remain anonymous. Do not intentionally exploit any discovered
vulnerability and do not share details of unpatched vulnerabilities with
third parties.

